Chapter One
Kolong or possibly Kolon (referring to a place or a person's name)
In Itania time, it was 4:30 in the morning.  Colonel Koren disliked getting up so early.  Mainly because he had to wake up the rest of the platoon.  He quietly got out of bed, put on his combat uniform, slipped on his tactical vest, and tidied up the things in the storage cabinet, carefully picked up a small special box.  He slung his rifle over his shoulder, hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt.  The helmet was equipped with a full set of equipment, including an oxygen tank, a visor, and other necessary items.  After checking the ammunition pouch, he quietly left the barracks, his boots stepping on the mud and ice, making a creaking sound.
He took out his lighter from his jacket pocket, and then pulled out a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a light puff and then opened the door. In the past week, he had to think of every trick in the book to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the pre-set alarm clock because half the time it didn't ring, and all that came out of the speaker was a faint buzzing sound.
"Won't you wake them up?" Colonel turned around, seeing Ensign Nemiuchin walk over.
“Yes, it is.” Colin replied.
"What are you planning to do this time?"
Colon hadn't had a chance to answer, the door opened, Harris, Krees and a few others rushed out, all of them already dressed and ready.
“Good morning,” Kreis said.
"What woke you up?" Colonel asked.
"First of all, we really don't want to see what method you'll use to wake everyone up today. Secondly, the first team to wake up can have priority to eat breakfast," said a soldier named Raviq. "You know how bad those breakfasts are."
Kolen said, "You're right, Corporal Ravi." He stretched out his hand and flipped the switch. The barracks was immediately filled with a piercing siren sound. He heard loud shouting and chaotic footsteps coming from inside.
"Oh my, Valturie," Nemitsch said. "I thought they must have learned to wake up with you by now."
"It's what my new recruits have done," Colonel ironed, nodding towards Harris, Krees, and Ravik. "But, as I'm sure the sergeant in charge and the platoon sergeant know, not to get up before the men."
A few seconds later, the rest of the platoon's soldiers all came running out, all properly dressed and ready to go. Some new recruits looked half asleep, while others appeared furious.
"Good morning, everyone," Colin said with enthusiasm.
"Honestly, sir, why did you wake us up in that manner?" a sergeant of the special forces asked.
"Those ordinary alarm clocks are just trash," Colin said. "And Daybreak never hits the snooze button."
"Along with your personal belongings," Colonel continued to say. As a lieutenant and deputy commander of the platoon, he had the responsibility to assist Lieutenant Borelin Xau to supervise and lead the platoon. "We won't be coming back. Sergants and lieutenants, give your men and yourselves 15 minutes to do a final check and pack up the rations you'll need today."
Exodus team members quickly scattered. They were part of the 2nd Assault Battalion, 2nd Marine Division. Before being merged, they were originally two independent platoons, Cohort and Dagger. This was an elite unit, and Keren's feelings about promotion to lieutenant were complex, with many reasons for this.
Kolen and the First Sergeant Nimitz walked side by side down the brightly lit base roads, where the streetlights were powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, which helped them avoid enemy bombers. In order to hit them, Daybreak had begun using "Furry Mice" tactics in the air and on the ground.
"Ah, a new day, and a new hell to conquer," Nimitch said with a chuckle. "Where are they sending us this time?"
"In front of Ianloos' fortress, we're on the frontline base. We've been sent to assist the ground assault," Colonel said, taking a drag on his cigarette. He somewhat blamed Kress for getting him hooked on cigarette, but thinking about the past year and the countless battles they'd been through, he let it go."
"It's ghastly. The front situation is tight," Nimitz whispered. "All the news coming out from here is about 'supporting the war, assisting the Kurgan front,' why not support the Khouran front?"
"That's right, brother," Kael said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. "We're going with the first armored platoon, so we won't have to walk. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Commander Xiao wanted us to hitch a ride?" Nimitch asked in some surprise.
"True, I have to say he's not as bad as I imagined. I mean, he's not great, but he's not repulsive either."
Kolen raised his thumb and index finger, pressing the microphone on his throat, while moving his backpack onto his back. "Exodus is to leave all units, assemble at the Western Vehicle Depot after completing the task. We will depart at 05:00 with the First Armored Company."
Every few seconds, he would receive their replies.  Harris, Kress, and Ravik were all NCOs of lower ranks when they first arrived, but since they had undergone basic training on Earth, the four of them had been close friends. It felt like it had been ages since they had met, given that it had been less than two years. They were all platoon sergeants, but since the day before, after the Daybreak sniper had hit the point man and withdrawn due to injury, Kress had started taking over the second squad.
As they reached the vehicle section, Colonel Kollen and Nimitz's gaze fell on about eight battle-ready Kronos tanks and four Seekha armored cars. The crew members scurried about, ensuring their war machines were in order. Kollen quickly spotted Lieutenant Boradin, who was in conversation with the commander of the armor platoon.
"Ensign Nimitz……Lieutenant Wartell……" he said, slowing his pace, Lieutenant Shaw looked at Colonel's holstered pistol, then looked up. "Should the squad be ready by now?"
